  "summary": "Poirot informs Hastings that his life is nearing its end and warns that a clever individual known as \"X\" might attempt to hasten his death for personal gain. Poirot reveals he has made arrangements for Hastings to succeed him, leaving physical clues in a locked briefcase that will eventually lead Hastings to the truth.\n\nFollowing a dinner at Styles Manor with Mrs. Letreul, Dr. Franklin, and Nurse Crewe, the group plays cards. Later, Hastings visits Poirot with Norton, who intends to lend Hastings a book. During the night, Hastings is awakened by a noise and observes Norton returning to his room in striped pajamas and locking his door. This sight causes Hastings unease, as he recalls the mysterious disappearance of Poirot's room key.\n\nThe next morning, Poirot appears exhausted and ill. He reveals that Norton reported seeing two people, though Poirot refuses to disclose their identities immediately, stating he wishes to remember the details first. While Poirot claims the case is essentially over, he remains melancholy. After breakfast, Hastings encounters an energetic Boyd Carlington in the garden. They observe that while other windows at the manor are open following a storm, Norton's window remains shut. Concerned that Norton may be ill, they decide to check on him.",
